Here is the fixed unit test:

```java
package original;

import org.junit.Test;
import static org.junit.Assert.*;

public class IsBoredTest {

    @Test
    public void testIsBored() {
        String s = "I am bored. Are you bored? I am not bored!";
        int expectedCount = 2;
        int actualCount = IsBored.isBored(s);
        assertEquals(expectedCount, actualCount);
    }

    @Test
    public void testIsBored_NoBoredOccurrences() {
        String s = "This is a test sentence.";
        int expectedCount = 0;
        int actualCount = IsBored.isBored(s);
        assertEquals(expectedCount, actualCount);
    }

    @Test
    public void testIsBored_EmptyString() {
        String s = "";
        int expectedCount = 0;
        int actualCount = IsBored.isBored(s);
        assertEquals(expectedCount, actualCount);
    }

    @Test
    public void testIsBored_NullString() {
        String s = null;
        int expectedCount = 0;
        int actualCount = IsBored.isBored(s);
        assertEquals(expectedCount, actualCount);
    }

    @Test
    public void testIsBored_MultipleBoredOccurrences() {
        String s = "I am bored. Are you bored? I am bored too!";
        int expectedCount = 2;
        int actualCount = IsBored.isBored(s);
        assertEquals(expectedCount, actualCount);
    }
}
```

The error in the unit test was due to a `NullPointerException` occurring in the `testIsBored_NullString` test case. This happened because the `isBored` method was not handling the case when the input string `s` is `null`. To fix this, I have updated the `isBored` method to handle the `null` case and return 0.
